<h1>Schedule</h1>
<%- if @plan.empty? -%>
<p class="muted">No schedule configured — set <span class="mono">schedule:</span> in your
config (or run <span class="mono">pgkeeper connect</span>), then a
<span class="mono">maintenance:</span> block to schedule verify and prune too.</p>
<%- else -%>
<table>
  <tr><th>Job</th><th>Scope</th><th>Schedule</th><th>Cron</th><th>Next runs (UTC)</th></tr>
  <%- @plan.each do |row| -%>
  <tr>
    <td>
      <%= pill(row.action, "") %>
      <%- unless row.flags.empty? -%><span class="mono muted"><%= h(row.flags.join(' ')) %></span><%- end -%>
    </td>
    <td><%= h(row.scope) %></td>
    <td><%= h(row.cadence) %></td>
    <td class="mono"><%= h(row.cron) %></td>
    <td>
      <%- if row.next_runs.empty? -%>
      <span class="muted">—</span>
      <%- else -%>
      <%- row.next_runs.each do |t| -%>
      <div class="mono"><%= h(fmt_time(t)) %></div>
      <%- end -%>
      <%- end -%>
    </td>
  </tr>
  <%- end -%>
</table>
<p class="muted">This is the plan resolved from your config — the same one
<span class="mono">pgkeeper schedule print</span> shows. It only fires once it's wired up:
<span class="mono">pgkeeper schedule install</span> (crontab lines) or
<span class="mono">--systemd</span> (timer units), or <span class="mono">pgkeeper daemon</span>
in a container. To run a job right now, use the <a href="/actions">actions</a> page.</p>
<%- end -%>
